The mental model.

When a container starts on a normal, non-host network, the kernel gives it a network namespace of its own. That namespace has its own network interfaces, usually just a loopback and a single virtual ethernet device, its own eye-pee addresses, its own routing table, its own firewall rules, and its own set of open ports. From inside, it looks like a tiny isolated machine on a network.

From the host's side, the container's ethernet device is one end of a virtual ethernet pair, and the other end plugs into a linux bridge on the host. For the default network that bridge is called docker zero, and for user-defined networks it is a separate bridge per network. Picture two containers on the same bridge, each with its own address, both wired into docker zero, which in turn is wired to the host's real network card for outbound traffic. The bridge is essentially a layer-two switch in software, so containers on the same bridge talk to each other directly, while reaching the outside world goes through network address translation.

Three consequences fall out of this, and they explain most networking confusion. First, local-host inside a container means the container itself, not the host, so to reach the host from a container you use a real eye-pee or a special name on docker desktop. Second, containers on the same user-defined bridge can reach each other by container name, because the daemon runs an embedded d-n-s resolver inside each container's namespace. And third, inbound traffic from the outside world has to be deliberately routed in, which is exactly what publishing a port does.
